    44‚Üí * A `Matcher` is an object implementing the match
    45‚Üí * protocol. It must define a `symbols.matcher` property
    46‚Üí * which returns an object with a `match()` method, taking
    47‚Üí * the input value and returning whether the pattern matches
    48‚Üí * or not, along with optional selections.
    50‚Üíexport interface Matcher<
    51‚Üí  input,
    52‚Üí  narrowed,
    53‚Üí  // Type of what this pattern selected from the input
    54‚Üí  matcherType extends MatcherType = 'default',
    55‚Üí  selections extends SelectionType = None,
    56‚Üí  // Type to exclude from the input union because
    57‚Üí  // it has been fully matched by this pattern
    58‚Üí  excluded = narrowed
    59‚Üí> {
    60‚Üí  [matcher](): MatcherProtocol<
    61‚Üí    input,
    62‚Üí    narrowed,
    63‚Üí    matcherType,
    64‚Üí    selections,
    65‚Üí    excluded
    66‚Üí  >;
    67‚Üí  // only used for array matchers
    68‚Üí  [symbols.isVariadic]?: boolean;
    69‚Üí}
   132‚Üíexport interface Override<a> {
   133‚Üí  [symbols.override]: a;
   134‚Üí}
   147‚Üí * `Pattern<a>` is the generic type for patterns matching a value of type `a`. A pattern can be any (nested) javascript value.
   148‚Üí *
   149‚Üí * They can also be wildcards, like `P._`, `P.string`, `P.number`,
   150‚Üí * or other matchers, like `P.when(predicate)`, `P.not(pattern)`, etc.
   151‚Üí *
   152‚Üí * [Read the documentation for `P.Pattern` on GitHub](https://github.com/gvergnaud/ts-pattern#patterns)
   153‚Üí *
   154‚Üí * @example
   155‚Üí * const pattern: P.Pattern<User> = { name: P.string¬Ý}
   157‚Üíexport type Pattern<a = unknown> = unknown extends a
   158‚Üí  ? UnknownValuePattern
   159‚Üí  : KnownPattern<a>;
